Overview
========

Libdivecomputer is a cross-platform and open source library for
communication with dive computers from various manufacturers.

The official web site is:

  http://www.libdivecomputer.org/

The sourceforge project page is:

  http://sourceforge.net/projects/libdivecomputer/

Installation
============

On UNIX-like systems (including Linux, Mac OS X, MinGW), use the
autotools based build system. Run the following commands from the top
directory (containing this file) to configure, build and install the
library and utilities:

  $ ./configure
  $ make
  $ make install

If you downloaded the libdivecomputer source code directly from the git
source code repository, then you need to create the configure script as
the first step:

  $ autoreconf --install

To uninstall libdivecomputer again, run:

  $ make uninstall

Building on Windows x64 (MinGW)
================================

This fork includes a CMake build for Windows x64 using the MinGW-W64
toolchain (tested with WinLibs GCC 16.x, UCRT).

Prerequisites:

  - WinLibs MinGW-W64: https://winlibs.com/
    (extract to e.g. D:\work\winlibs\mingw64)
  - CMake (included in the WinLibs bundle)

The build requires two submodules (already initialized in this repo):

  deps/libusb  -- libusb-1.0 (USB transport)
  deps/hidapi  -- hidapi     (USBHID transport, Windows native HID API)

After cloning, initialize the submodules:

  $ git submodule update --init --recursive

Then configure and build from a build directory:

  $ mkdir build\mingw64 && cd build\mingw64
  $ D:\work\winlibs\mingw64\bin\cmake.exe -G "MinGW Makefiles" ^
      -DCMAKE_C_COMPILER=D:\work\winlibs\mingw64\bin\gcc.exe ^
      -DCMAKE_RC_COMPILER=D:\work\winlibs\mingw64\bin\windres.exe ^
      -DCMAKE_MAKE_PROGRAM=D:\work\winlibs\mingw64\bin\mingw32-make.exe ^
      ..\..
  $ D:\work\winlibs\mingw64\bin\mingw32-make.exe -j4

Output artifacts in build\mingw64\:

  libdivecomputer.dll      -- shared library (link against this at runtime)
  liblibdivecomputer.dll.a -- import library (link against this at build time)

Enabled transports in the Windows CMake build:

  Serial    -- native Win32 serial port API
  IrDA      -- Windows IrDA socket API (af_irda.h)
  Bluetooth -- Windows Bluetooth RFCOMM socket API (ws2bth.h)
  USB       -- libusb-1.0 (WinUSB + UsbDk backends, loaded dynamically)
  USBHID    -- hidapi with native Windows HID API (hid.dll, loaded dynamically)

